Assessment¶

  • There are miising values in the dataset
  • Start_time column data type is object instead of datetime
  • End_time column data type is object instead of datetime
  • Start_station_id data type is float instead of object
  • End_station_id data type is float instead of object
  • Bike_id data type is integer instead of object
  • Member_birth_year is float instead of datetime
  • Coordinate points columns are available but not distance between the start and end point
  • Member_birth_year can be used to compute the age of members

Issue¶

Coordinate points columns are available but not distance between the start and end point

define¶

  • Compute distance in km from the start point to the end point using the coordinate columns

code¶

In [15]:
# Create function that converts geographical coordinated to distance in kilometers
def haversine(row):
    """
    Calculate the great circle distance between two points 
    on the earth (specified in decimal degrees)
    """
    # convert decimal degrees to radians
    lon1 = row['start_station_longitude']
    lat1 = row['start_station_latitude']
    lon2 = row['end_station_longitude']
    lat2 = row['end_station_latitude']

    lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2 = map(radians, [lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2])
    # haversine formula 
    dlon = lon2 - lon1 
    dlat = lat2 - lat1 
    a = sin(dlat/2)**2 + cos(lat1) * cos(lat2) * sin(dlon/2)**2
    c = 2 * asin(sqrt(a)) 
    km = 6367 * c
    return km
In [16]:
fordgobike_clean['distance'] = fordgobike_clean.apply(haversine, axis=1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are about 161452 individual rides in the dataset after wrangling with 18 features such as duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip most of which are numerical, there were however some categorical data such as user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip and distance, distance and age

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

i'm interested in a number of features such as ;

  • How long does the average trip take
  • Other factors that may influence average trip duration such as the user_type, member_gender, distance covered or age

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the the distance between the start station of the bike to the end station will play a significant role in predicting the duration of rides. Also, the Age of the rider may have some influence on the duration and distance covered while the member gender may also play a role in determininig ride duration. i do not however think that the user type play any significant role if any.

# Create boxplot of numerical variables against categorical variaibles
def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ This helps in Creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid as quickly as possible.
        the function should be passed as an Argument into Seaborn.PairGrid.map
        
        Args:
             x: x
             y: y
        kwargs: This take any keyword parameters that is acceptable by seaborn.boxplot
    """
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [11.69, 8.27])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = fordgobike_clean, y_vars = ['duration_sec', 'distance'], x_vars = ['member_gender', 'user_type'], 
                aspect = 1.5)
g.map(boxgrid);

Conclusions¶

Fordgobike data that includes information on individual bike rides were explored by first looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest which is the duration in seconds that it takes for riders to complete a ride and it showed a distribution with long tail which was subsequently transformed to log, each of the other variable of interests were also explored individually as well as collectively. The relationship between duration and other variables such as distance covered, gender, user type and age showed a positive correlation between duration and distance across the gender and user type even though the female gender had a higher median distance covered and consequently duration used while there were not significant correlations found between age and distance covered or duration
